  "explanation_shown_to_user": "With a working six-count and four hearts, the negative double is the textbook way to stay in the auction: it finds the 4-4 heart fit when partner has one and lets a strong notrump with good diamonds convert to penalty at favorable colors for the defense. The catch is the shape, since only two spades means partner's routine 2S response lands the partnership in a seven-card fit with no graceful exit, and 9865 of diamonds contributes nothing to a penalty pass. Passing concedes 2D quietly, which is fine when the deal is a misfit, and it is not always the end of the story: a short-diamond opener will often reopen with a double, letting this hand show the hearts after all. But when opener is obliged to sit, a heart partscore that belongs to your side may vanish. Partner still holds 15-17, so selling out at the two level cheaply is not automatic. The simulation will say whether the flawed double or the meek pass loses less over the long run.\n\u26a0 X deviates from the card: the negative double implies four cards in both unbid majors; only two spades here",
